segments.text: Having Waco as a court trip also.
But I mean, then even after that, because the court trips then became Dallas and Fort Worth, Austin and Houston.
I don't know.
I never did figure out which one was where, but they had a court trip.
I never was on one of them.
I do know that they went into your eyes one day.

for the Corps trip, and they had a whole empty section of the Corps bleachers up there, and the Corps didn't have that kind of money that they were charging for those things, and there was all these empty seats up there.
The boys, if you take 500 or 1,000 of them,
During your freshman year, do you remember going to some out-of-town games?
No, I never went to, very seldom went to out-of-town.
Now, the WTAW was the first one.
that brought the games to any.
And that was done in the air dome.
And what they did, they used the...
So you're saying the out-of-town games would be broadcast back to the air dome?
They got some people over there at the game, and they got the Western Union to
give them a teletype.
And they would send it right there, and then this guy would get up there and read it off, you know.
That's the way we found out about it at first.
So did y'all go over there and have fun during the game?
Oh, we'd go.
No, it was in the air dome.
No, I mean in the air dome.
Did you go over there?
We just
The only place I, the only time I was much in that air dome was early, they used to have some, some very glory pictures of movies of people
on boats, you know, fighting and cutting guys open and this thing and that thing, you know.

So what had happened was that my dad and mother would sit there on the first row to the left over there and there was a door right there, a great big open door and there was clothes and so it would get to be like that and we three would jump up and run out.
And then my mother gave us a high sign, we can come back in.
That's what the early days, the real early days of that thing was.
Now when you were a fish, was the Aggie slang already in use?
Oh yeah, the Aggie slang.
You had to wear a band, a white band.
to identify yourself as a fish, describe the kinds of uniforms y'all wore.
What did the uniforms look like that y'all were issued then?
They were wool, standard wool.
What colors?
Green.
No khaki?
No khaki.
No, no, no, no khaki.
They were what you would call, what did you call them, green?
Was it pretty well World War I style?
They had leggings, but they didn't have to wind them.
The first one, yeah, that's right.
The first ones I got, they just buttoned up on the side, on the outside.
Now, did a freshman, a fish, wear leggings?
Yeah.
And is that what you wore to class?
Yeah.
Shoes, what color shoes?
Brown or black?
Brown.
Brown.
What kind of hat?
Oh, you had a big one.
Freshman, and you wore that every day?
Yeah, but you couldn't put the strap behind your head.
Why?
You were an upperclassman.
Ah, so you had to... You had to wear it down on the front.
And you couldn't put it back there like that.
That's the first thing I learned.
All right, now, when you did anything on the campus during the daytime, did you wear your uniform?
Yeah.
But then when you went home for supper, you took it off?
Yeah.
Now, did you come back to the campus much at night?
And if so, why?
They had some different...
functions there.
One of them, the reason I remember this is because my cousin was living with us in 1930.
He was a year ahead of me.
And he entered the math contest.
They had a math contest there.
And if you won the math contest, you got the gold watch.
They gave you gold.
And I remember he came home, and in our house, the living room was here, and the big old double doors, and then there's a stairway going upstairs.
And he came through the door there and started up the stairs, and Dad asked him,
How'd you come out?
He just held up that watch.
He was a genius at math.
He understood it.
I understood math, but I never could make it function.
Now, as you and your buddies were going to class, did you all have to whip out to every upperclassman as you walked along the sidewalk?
Whatever they had, we did it.
It didn't make any difference.
Then you had to learn their name?
No.
You didn't?
I never did learn.
The people I knew were the ones that were in class with me in the A engineering, or some of the students that I was with all the time.
Describe a typical day, class day for you.
You got up at what time, ate breakfast when, and where did you go?
You just had to figure out, you had to go figure out which room you were going to be in.
When you, when you registered, you went and figured out where you had to go, and they had room to specify for you.
But, but living where you lived, what time did you get up and have breakfast?
I don't remember anything.
Their mother had that thing on that table back in the back.
And you walked over to the campus.
Either walked over or Dad took us.
Okay.
And during the day, did you go to class regularly?
Or did you skip class?
No, we didn't skip class.
So you went to class regularly.
If you had an hour that wasn't scheduled.
We went over to the.
to the library.
I spent many hours in that library.
Was there also a place where you could go and maybe take a brief snooze?
No.
Where did you go to get a cup of coffee or a Coca-Cola?
Why?
Oh, yeah, they had a
On the north side of the Y, in that rounded part there, a couple of men had a refreshment outfit.
On the south side of that thing was a barber shop.
That's where I went to get my hair cut.
Now, was there a pool table also?
No.
No.
There was no pool.
I don't remember any pool table being on any of them campers.
Did anybody go to Northgate or Southgate to get a soft drink?
Northgate they might have, but there wasn't anything there.
All there was out there was that Kyle Billy, which is on that side, and the one that's where Lupo's is, I think that's the Kyle Billy.
But there was another one over there, the red Billy, and that was about all that was there.
Except Luke and Charlie's, which was in a, where the bookstore is.
And it was just a big, all-open store.
And you could buy anything you wanted there.
I don't remember they even had...
The only thing I know we had was a Delaware Punch.
We would like that stuff.
So, I don't know.
You had soft drinks, but they had to be in a bottle.
And it cost a nickel.
Did you and your buddies drink coffee much?
You had several waters.
You see, the water was exactly the same then as it is now.
except that you had this fault line up here just north of Bryan.
And as that water poured through that salt line, you picked up your sulfur.
Then they took the water, all the water came off, and they ran it through the condensers in the power plant to heat it up.
And then they had a big spray pond out there just south of where it was now the power plant.
It was about a couple of acres in there.
And they sprayed it up, trying to get rid of the sulfur.
But it would still turn the silver.
Now, see, we didn't have plastic stuff in those days.
You had silver.
And it turned?
Turned black.
Around the household, that was one of the things you had to do about every month.
You had to go down there and help them take the silver polish and polish off the silver of them.
Back to people, Tommy Mayo was the director of the library.
Describe him, please.
All I knew about him was he took care of his mother.
And he did that to her.
his detriment, as far as I'm concerned.
I mean, no, not to, but he did never get a family, if I know of.
Was he, was the library a pleasant place?
Oh, it was quite nice.
The, what do you call it, the first one up here?
The Cushing.
I was sitting in that reading room many, many hours.
About how late at night was it open?
Do you remember?
It was open quite a long way.
I never was there much at night.
Did you study at home?
No.
I was

at that time my blood sugar was such that I was between a normal person and a diabetic and they mother and dad insisted you eat three meals a day three square meals a day and therefore I never I couldn't when after
I might watch, might do something.
Of course, we had to take care of the cows, too.
That was a chore, always, and I had to do that.
And so then, I was always out.
And I finally, after the last ten years, I finally conquered it.
All right, back to another great person on campus, Mr. Cashin.
Yeah.
Describe him, please.
Very fine man.
I don't know.
I know, I remember what he looked like, but I...
Describe him, what he looked like.
Oh, I don't know.
He was
son is in the church and I see him every time I go in there.
Now, did he look more, did Jim or Red more favor their father?
Red.
He wasn't as big a man as Jim was.
See, back in those days, we never did get people that were that big.
No, everybody was smaller.
You know why, don't you?
Didn't eat as much.
What they ate wasn't any good.
And we didn't, we didn't gain as much weight in the middle as... And people did more manual labor.
Well, either labor wouldn't make any difference, but you take bread,
And they came along when I was in high school or there, and they said, now the white bread, they've taken all the menu and the stuff out of it.
They knew they'd milled it all out.
And so then they said, well, you've got to have whole wheat bread.
So I had the whole wheat bread.
When I went to...
Around high school, I'd take my lunch with me.
Whole wheat bread all the time.
Now, you didn't bring your lunch while you were at A&M.
You didn't bring your lunch to the campus.
You went back home to eat lunch every day?
One of us was going back home all the time.
Was there, that freshman year, did you have some teachers, some instructors that were important to you?
Some that you, who?
In the math department, his name was Martin.
What made him special?
He taught me how to handle balls.
Well, it's just plain old arithmetic.
You know, he'd ask you,
multiply this 13 times this number here and how would you go about it so you wouldn't, you could do it in your brain.
He did a lot more than that than anybody I ever saw.
Who did you turn to for academic advice?
Dad.
Dad?
Dad.
Did he give you any guidelines?
Oh yeah.
When he said one day, he says, son, you're going to be in this.
I was teaching at Tarleton.
You're going to be in this business.
You've got to get your master's degree.
And I knew exactly where I was going.
I would stay in college.
And so I went up there, and they got me with a
Well, a fellowship with a steel company.
And we were studying the penetration of steel roof, the heat penetration of steel roof.
I built some houses out there.
I did the whole works.
I got a whole thesis on it, but it was tough.
It's not like it is today.
Back to your freshman year, where did you all have Yale practice?
Off the steps of the YMCA.
Was there a midnight Yale practice then?
But did they also have other Yale practices?
Did you have more than one a week?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, they would have several.
But there was not a Yale practice held in the stadium?
Not until later years.
See, that stadium wasn't built until 29.
Yeah.
All that was there before 29, there was a set of steel bleachers and then a football field.
And that football field was not drained.
And what happened was that if you played on it a little while,
the last 20 yards would be nothing but a mud hole.
Where you can.
So they came to dad.
He wrote, he has a book on land drainage and reclamation.
And so they came to him and they said, can you drain that field?
And he said, yes.
And so they said, you go over there, and you go.
And so he went to work at it.
But Dad was one of them that had his men around him, that he knew what they could do.
And so I think it was Altamira that he used.
Anyways, a student went over there and was working at it, laying it all out.
And the official from Adelaide Republic said, well, I thought you were going to do this.
That student knows as much about it as I do.
They were paying him 75 cents an hour.
They paid that student.
That was good paying those years.
That was excellent.
Yes.
So you understand?
That's one thing.
Did you say that after the stadium was built, after Kyle Field Stadium was built in 29, did they start having Yale practice over there the night before a game?
They could have.
They used it that way when they were closed in.
They actually had...
They used it for several, where they had concerts.
Bob Hope was there in a concert.
And we had a woman here who was, she had a voice like you wouldn't believe.
Kate Smith?
What?
Kate Smith?
God Bless America, Kate Smith?
No, I'm talking about a person.
Oh, oh.
One right here.
Oh.
Oh.
One of the Butler girls.
One of the Butler wives.
I can still hear him up there on that stage.
And she was there, and she was there.
Man, she could sing.
And so he didn't do anything, but
but just tease the crowd.
And he said, do you believe she can do that?
So she would sing another song.
And that went on for a couple hours.
I mean, Bob Hope right there, we paid him good money.
Of course, he had some ad libs in between and all that, you know.
It was a real good show.
Do you remember when you first went to Silver Taps?
No.
Did you go to Silver Taps when you were a little kid?
No.
Was it held then?
I don't think so.
They might have held it in the context of the military.
but it wasn't every time.
Do you remember going to silver taps then after you were in the Corps?
No, I never ever went to silver taps.
I know they do it now and that sort of thing, but I never did.
When you were a fish, did you have to polish sully?
Was that tradition around then?
Oh, yeah, but you know what happened to Sully, don't you?
Well, when he was moved, that statue was moved up from the, it came on the railroad.
It moved straight up that road in there, and they were getting ready to set him on the, on that, uh, uh,
Pedestal?
Yeah, pedestal.
It's not marble.
It's the other... Oh, boy.
Yeah, it's not marble.
It's a pedestal made out of rock and ground.
Granite?
Granite.
He was sitting there.
And it was the night before Easter.
When the Corps went into Guy Hall, Sully was behind the poker.
Did you see that?
No, I didn't before I was there.
About when was that?
That was probably whenever that thing was moved in there.
But when would that have been?
I would say it was about 1916 or something like that.
Okay.
Now, how far back does Guyon Hall go?
When was it built?
Do you remember?
It was one of the first that was around.
There was several other buildings there that were chapels.
Mm-hmm.
one where Hart, we used it for a gun, a shooting gallery.
And I remember that because, but the trouble they had with Guyon Hall was that the back end fell off of it.
Now, was Guyon Hall here when y'all moved here?
Well, it was.
It was here.
They didn't have that trouble then, but later on they did.
They had to go jack that thing back up again.
And nobody knew how Sully happened to be moved over?
No, when the Corps did something like that, you never found out how it was.
And there wasn't any use to try.
Do you remember going to Muster, Aggie Muster, April 21st?
When you were a fish, did you help with bonfire?
Yes.
Describe.
Except that, yeah, I helped with a little bit.
How long did y'all work on bonfire then?
How long did it take?
Well, you see, bonfire, as we know it today,
It was not that.
The bonfire was nothing but crating.
Now that I know.
And the reason you don't know is that we had to use those same trees that they're putting in the bonfire for our fuel, for cooking, and heating the house.
And to burn up the crating and all the other trash, everybody was glad to get rid of it.
Yeah.
Am I correct that people would put their stuff out in the front for y'all to...
I don't remember anything about that.
I don't remember anything about that.
But I do know that they carried it off down there near the Old Britain's Tower.
They moved that big stone for the...
World War II.
They moved it off of where the home was at the time and they had it right in there.
What they were concerned with was they had those three houses over there where Dr. Dean Kyle and let's see, Dean Kyle and Dr. Marsteller and the
house doctor, whatever he was.
They were concerned about that.
Now, am I correct also that quite often they used the railroad push carts, those flat carts to carry the trash?
I would imagine so.
They were used for everything.
And how long did it take for y'all to get all that stuff?
Was it three months or two weekends or what?
Well, I think they just had a pile out there that they were building on all the time.
I mean, and they just kept it there, and they just finally, everybody would pitch in and
give a little bit, and that's what, that's the way it went.
And about how many people came to Bonfire?
Oh, the whole thing, you know, the Corps came.
Did, did your family come over?
Did everybody in the community come over?
We, yeah, we went out there and looked at it.
And even, you know, when it was over on the, the big ones over in, on Simpson Field, they had some pretty good-sized ones over there that were actually trees.
And then I think they did damage the roof, I understand, on the Memorial Student Center one night.
But am I correct that until World War II, there were not trees, logs, it was the packing material and rubbish?
No, I would say even before that, before they could use trees.
See, the thing that you've got to remember is that gas came in here in 1928.
That changed the whole thing up.
Okay, okay.
See, because before that, when we lived up on the campus from 1919 to 1924, it was common for Dad to get 15 cords of wood back of that house
And then they had to have a guy come in there with a forged tractor with a big old saw on it and saw it up.
I mean, the 18-inch length or 24-inch length, depending on how you wanted to fuel your fireplace or your...
When the gas came in, well, it all walked out.
I mean, we had in the Irish...
